    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0001">Downing</placeName>
                        <choice>
                            <abbr>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                            </abbr>
                            <expan>December</expan>
                        </choice> 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1781</dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I had the happiness of being brought up under <persName ref="pe0341 pe0342">parents</persName> who instilled into
                    me early, fit notions of the dispensations of providence. I <del>am</del> have
                    in consequence been thereby enabled to rejoice at every piece of good fortune
                    that has befallen us, &amp; bear resignedly the bad: of which Heaven at present
                    has been pleased to pour down a very large portion indeed.</p>
                <p>I shall continue in the Country as it becomes a man who h<gap unit="chars" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>
                    <supplied>a</supplied>s on him large
                    dependencies: people who are not indifferent to my absence or presence. I
                    rejoice that I have some amusements that at <del>d</del>times drive away the
                    thoughts of our Calamities, &amp; those amusements I shall doubly cultivate.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="pe0338">Bartollozi</persName> by dint of an attorneyâ€™s
                    quil returned the drawings: one he had begun to etch: the others untouched. I
                    hear a bad account of him.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="pe0014">Moses</persName> is working hard for you: but
                    there is no finishing till spring: Pray remember you cannot bind up <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0012">snowdon</title>
                    </bibl> as
                    there is a second part to appear. which I shall endeavour to bring out by
                    Christmas. 1782<note type="editorial">A Journey to Snowdon (1781) was vol. 2,
                        part 1, of Pennant's A Tour in Wales. Vol. 2, part II, appeared in 1783
                        (this also subdivided into 'The Continuation of the Journey' and 'From
                        Downing to Montgomery and Shrewsbury'). LINK TO WORKS LIST: Continuation of
                        the Journey (London: Henry Hughes, 1783): generic</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am <lb/>most faithfully <lb/>
                        <choice>
                        <abbr>Y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                            </abbr>
                        <expan>Yours</expan>
                    </choice>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">
                            <choice>
                                <abbr>T.</abbr>
                                <expan>Thomas</expan>
                            </choice>Pen<gap unit="chars" quantity="4" reason="illegible"/>
                            <supplied>nant</supplied>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P.S. I enclose a rough list of the drawings in <bibl type="authorial">
                            <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0012">vol. I. II.</title>
                        </bibl>
                       <note type="editorial">Vol. 1, part II, of A tour in Wales would be A
                            Journey to Snowdon (1781). LINK TO WORKS LIST: A Journey to Snowdon
                            (London: printed by Henry Hughes, 1781): generic</note> Pray return it
                        after you have copied it.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
